  "text": "All cases had clear botanical hepatotoxicity caused by pyrrolizidine alkaloids, such as Gynura segetum, mushroom tea, and traditional remedies. Color Doppler ultrasound (US) was used for first-line diagnosis of SOS, and enhanced computed tomography (CT) and/or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) were performed in all patients to confirm the US findings. SOS was diagnosed clinically referring to the Seattle or Baltimore criteria [CITATION_1] , the occurrence of two or more of the following events before day 21 after hemopoietic progenitor cell administration: hyperbilirubinemia (>34.2 mol/L or >2 mg/dL), ascites or sudden weight gain (>5% of baseline body weight), and painful hepatomegaly. No other explanation for these signs and symptoms (septicemia, cyclosporin toxicity, heart failure, hepatitis, etc.) could be present at the time of diagnosis.",
